				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Starting a cat bard....<a name="4382"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 14 03 10:23 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Being a 51 Bard who made some very large mistakes when first I made my character,( I think I went for str as I recall for stats), take these things into Consideration.
<br />

<br />
Str will factor somewhat into your DPS, though not nearly as much as you might think, as we ARE Bards, we aren't going to be big on getting many Str items in the long run, so a few points of Str added in the beginning is not going to have significant effect in the long run.
<br />

<br />
Dex/Agi. Both are useful for hitting, and determing Procs of weapons over all,and have minor affects on your AC. I personally shoot for these mostly. But that's because I have a decided preference for whipping out blades, clubs, whatever, and pounding on creatures while I sing, Crowd Control bard, I CAN be, Crowd Control Bard I do not LIKE to be.(And if you don't learn CC early, like I failed to do, you're going ot be hurting later when it's expected of you)
<br />

<br />
Sta. Sta. most people tend to ignore I've noticed. Extended running your butt off actually has an effect on your Sta. But I have yet to see it drop more than 30% over an extended period of running. So that doesn't seem to be as big a deal.
<br />

<br />
Why I WISH I had upgraded my stamina at character creaiton comes in with stunning. I get stunned, a LOT. Sta. helps with that. You get smashed a few times with low Sta. by a mob, and you can count on either standing there with your finger up your nose, or at the very least taking one or two revolutions aorund the world too look at things aorund you, while you are stunned.
<br />

<br />
Sta., get some Sta. if nothing else.
<br />

<br />
Cha? I'll be blunt. Yes, we use Cha. everyone uses it to some extent. It doesn't determine or Mez lengths, it doesn't help or hinder the length of our spells, or even determine whether or not our songs get resisted. The ONLY thing you will ultimately find that Cha does for you is avoid those annoying &quot;You missed a note&quot; messages.
<br />

<br />
Having had a 64 Mage, and a 65 Enchanter freind test a certain fact With a Cha 110 on the Mage, and a 250 or so on the Enchanter, both sold the same item to a vendor, to the tune of a 2 copper difference in price.
<br />

<br />
Once your Cha hits 110? Go looking for something else. It's not helping you. Bard, Enchanter or otherwise. IT's a waste of your time. This is apaprently a LONG standing bug of some type in EQ, don't ask me why.
<br />

<br />
I have recently been putting on gear that has actually NEGATIVELY been affecting my CHA, bad enough to turn my stat red(pushing it below my original numbers), and you know what? I haven't seen a single change in how effective my songs are. Makes you think, huh?
<br />

<br />
Me? Personally? What it boils down to is. Do you want a little extra DPS(and I do mean Little!) Go Str, Do you want some MINOR extra chance to hit ,and proc(and a VERY minor effect to AC?) Dex/Agi. Do you want to wear as little Cha enhancing gear as Possible? Put yer points into Cha, and be done with it. But above all, get some stamina, you really don't wanna be the spinning goof in combat loolking at the pretty world while you and your party are getting stomped by mobs.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">The hardest thing about being perfect, is dealing with all the inadequacies of others!</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
